            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>We want to show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\rightarrow ]]></fr:tex> preserves the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> property, that whenever both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> have the property, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \rightarrow  B]]></fr:tex> has it as well.
But if indeed both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> have the property, then we know that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(A)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(B)]]></fr:tex> can't be <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>, so we can set aside those rows and columns of the Dunn-Belnap table:</html:p>
